Team Section

Question

  • Overal Question: What are the factors that affect the avergage price or total volmue of hass avocados, and how can we understand these factors to generate more sales.

Data

## [1] -0.5099603
## [1] -0.3419494

Conclusion

  • Our objective was to manipulate data about avocado sales, in order to identify factors that will boost revenue for retailers. Together we created a general plot that compares the total volume of sales to the avergae price. We discovered that there was a separation in the plot when total volume reached 2e+07. The total volume that was greater than 2e+07 displayed a weak negative correlation. While the total volume less than 2e+07 showed a strong negative correlation. Individually we compared several factors that may affect the average price or total volume. From these plots, we noticed that region, type, and year affect both volume in sales and average price. The best corse of action to maximize profit is to keep avocado prices low while in season, and upsale on pairings such as tortilla chips and artisan bread. Total number of sales are highest when they are in season and cheaper prices will attract the consumers, while upselling on tortilla chips and bread will add on to their total cost, therefore increasing revenue.

I also used gather to combine the PLU codes for the avocadoes into one variable. Finally, I used filter to graph average price against the total volume in respect to a region, specifically SanDiego and Portland.

Aries Section

I wanted to compare the distribution of average price between conventional and organic avocados. So I used geom_density and faceted with type.

  • WHAT WERE YOUR FINDINGS?

Ethans Section

  • Findings: I asked the question of how the price of avocados changes throughout the year. I tidied the data by separating date into year, month, and day and transformed the data by grouping into month and summarising average price and volume stats. This graph displays the time of year (month) against the average price of avocadoes per unit, also illustrating the volume of avocados sold at every data point by size. The average price of avocados steadily increases throughout the year until October, when the prices begin to plummet. We can also see that the volume sold generally decreases as the price increases, which makes sense due to supply and demand and also suggests that avocados are freshest / most in season around September and October.
